      Dealers
   =20
 =20

In the olden days, there were two sorts of people who traded stocks or bond=
s for a living. We can call them =E2=80=9Cdealers=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cinv=
estors,=E2=80=9D though those terms are imperfect.
  [1]
 An investor is someone who buys stocks or bonds because she thinks they ar=
e a good investment, and sells them when she thinks they aren=E2=80=99t. Sh=
e does=C2=A0analysis, decides that Bond X is worth $80,=C2=A0sees it tradin=
g at $78, and goes out to buy some Bond X. When it trades up to $82, she se=
lls it. She makes her money by buying low and selling high, by predicting p=
rice trends or understanding fundamental value. Investors include ordinary =
retail investors, but mutual funds and hedge funds are also in this categor=
y. Their job is to buy stuff that they think will go up.
A dealer is the person the investors buy from=C2=A0and sell to. A dealer is=
 not looking to buy stocks or bonds that she thinks are a good investment, =
or to sell ones that she thinks are a bad investment. A bond dealer has som=
e list of bonds, and she is always willing to buy or sell each of those=C2=
=A0bonds. She is in a customer service business: Customers come to her look=
ing to buy or sell bonds, and she sells them the bonds they want to buy and=
 buys the bonds they want to sell. She makes money not by predicting price =
moves=C2=A0but by charging the customers (investors) a bit of money (called=
 the =E2=80=9Cspread=E2=80=9D) for each trade, buying from them at a lower =
price (her =E2=80=9Cbid=E2=80=9D) than she will sell to them (her =E2=80=9C=
offer=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cask=E2=80=9D).=C2=A0An investor thinks =E2=80=9C=
Bond X trades at $78 and is worth $80, so I will buy it.=E2=80=9D A dealer =
thinks =E2=80=9CBond X trades at $78, so I will buy it at $77.75 or sell it=
 at $78.25, whichever customers want.=E2=80=9D She doesn=E2=80=99t care wha=
t it=E2=80=99s worth. She cares about charging a bit more to sell than she =
pays to buy.=C2=A0
Investors could theoretically exist without dealers, and in some markets th=
ey do.
  [2]
 Investors who think that Bond X is worth $80 could just buy it from invest=
ors who think it=E2=80=99s worth $75, without a middleman. But in practice =
it is often helpful for there to be a middleman =E2=80=94=C2=A0a dealer =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0to =E2=80=9Cprovide liquidity.=E2=80=9D An investor who thinks =
Bond X is worth $80 probably wants to buy it=C2=A0now; an investor who thin=
ks it is worth $75 probably wants to sell it now.=C2=A0If they each come to=
 that conclusion at exactly the same time, they can trade with each other a=
nd that=E2=80=99s great. But if the seller decides to sell an hour before t=
he buyer decides to buy, it is helpful for there to be a middleman to buy f=
rom the seller and sell to the buyer. And the seller and buyer might each b=
e happy to pay $0.25 to get what they want when they want it.
In the olden days the dealer also provided an even more important service, =
which is that you knew where to find her. She was in the business of dealin=
g stocks or bonds. She made her money by having lots of customers. She adve=
rtised. She wanted you to call her to buy or sell bonds. Dealers were tradi=
tionally big brokerage firms and investment banks; they=C2=A0took big inves=
tors out for drinks to get to know them and win their business. Before, lik=
e, the internet, if some investor owned Bond X and thought it was worth $75=
 and wanted to sell it, and some other investor didn=E2=80=99t own Bond X a=
nd thought it was worth $80 and wanted to buy it, how would they=C2=A0know =
about each other? They wouldn=E2=80=99t. The investor who owned Bond X woul=
d call the dealer and sell to her, and the investor who wanted Bond X would=
 call the dealer and buy from her, because they had the dealer=E2=80=99s ph=
one number and knew she would be happy to buy or sell.
This was pretty true about the=C2=A0bond=C2=A0market, but less true about t=
he stock market. In the stock market there were (and are!)=C2=A0exchanges, =
where all the investors could meet up and buy and sell stocks. Investors co=
uld put=C2=A0orders into the stock market, saying =E2=80=9CI want to buy 10=
0 shares of Stock Y for $78,=E2=80=9D and if some other investor put an ord=
er in saying =E2=80=9CI want to sell 100 shares of Stock Y for $78=E2=80=9D=
 then they could=C2=A0trade with each other without involving a dealer at a=
ll. In practice stock exchanges normally do involve dealers, because there =
is often some imbalance between investors who want to buy and those who wan=
t to sell. But at least the exchange is a way of coordinating investor buye=
rs and investor sellers without having to=C2=A0call=C2=A0a dealer. If you w=
anted to sell a bond, you knew to call Bear Stearns or Lehman Brothers or w=
hoever; if you wanted to sell a New York Stock Exchange-listed=C2=A0stock, =
you knew to send an order to NYSE. (In practice you would do that through a=
=C2=A0broker=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0like Bear Stearns or Lehman Brothers =E2=
=80=94 because you couldn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0just stroll out on the floor of th=
e stock exchange, but still.)
But at least in the bond markets=C2=A0there was a pretty clear distinction =
between investors and dealers, which is that dealers advertised =E2=80=9CWe=
 Buy And Sell Bonds, Call Us!=E2=80=9D and investors did not.=C2=A0
But then the internet arrived, communications technology became vastly bett=
er, and everything went electronic. And now if you want to buy or sell bond=
s =E2=80=94=C2=A0or currencies, or interest-rate swaps, or cryptocurrencies=
, etc. =E2=80=94 you can often go to some electronic platform and put in an=
 order, just like you would on the stock exchange. And that platform will c=
ollect your orders, and the orders of lots of other people, and it will sho=
w the orders to everyone else on the platform
  [3]
=C2=A0and match up buyers and sellers. You don=E2=80=99t need to remember =
=E2=80=9CI want to sell bonds and I happen to know Morgan Stanley is in the=
 business of buying bonds, I should call them.=E2=80=9D You can just type =
=E2=80=9CSell bonds at $78=E2=80=9D into the electronic system and Morgan S=
tanley=C2=A0or BlackRock or Pimco or Fidelity or Citadel Securities or anyo=
ne else can buy them.
One possible outcome of this widespread electronification would be that inv=
estors would trade directly with investors and dealers would wither away in=
 bond (currency, swaps, crypto, etc.) markets. There would be no bid/ask sp=
reads, no intermediation; long-term owners would sell directly to other lon=
g-term owners at the mid-market=C2=A0price. You often see predictions like =
this, but they rarely come true. Even in open electronic all-to-all markets=
, dealers seem to provide some value by buying immediately when investors w=
ant to sell and selling immediately when investors want to buy. And investo=
rs are generally willing to pay a spread to get that immediacy.
But another, maybe more surprising outcome is that investors=C2=A0can be de=
alers now. If you run a hedge fund and try to buy bonds that you think will=
 go up, and you connect to an electronic trading platform and trade a lot o=
n it, you might notice some short-term opportunities. You know Bond X is tr=
ading at $78, you think it=E2=80=99s worth $80, but someone comes onto the =
platform with an order to buy a lot of Bond X. You might say =E2=80=9Cwell =
okay I=E2=80=99ll sell her some Bond X at $78.25, because she=E2=80=99s des=
perate to buy it now and will pay a bit more than the current market price,=
 and then in 10 minutes someone else will come along looking to sell it and=
 I=E2=80=99ll buy it back from him at $77.75 and make a quick 50 cents.=E2=
=80=9D Maybe you also have a big long-term investment position in Bond X th=
at you won=E2=80=99t close out until it hits $80, but you know that people =
make money by buying at the bid and selling at the offer and collecting the=
 spread, and you figure you can do a little bit of that too.
You can conceive of this as =E2=80=9Cdealing,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cmarket m=
aking,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Ccollecting the spread.=E2=80=9D You can do what=
 dealers do, and put=C2=A0orders=C2=A0into the electronic platform on both =
sides of the market: You can put in an order to buy 100 bonds at $77.75 and=
 another order to sell 100 bonds at $78.25 and hope that both of those orde=
rs will be executed and you=E2=80=99ll collect=C2=A0the spread. But you can=
 also conceive of it in other ways. You can think of it as just short-term =
day-trading, just spotting opportunities, just buying low (from someone loo=
king to unload bonds at a bit below the fair market price) and selling high=
 (minutes earlier or later, to someone looking to buy bonds at a bit above =
the fair market price). There is some continuum between =E2=80=9Cput in ord=
ers on both sides of the market to collect the spread=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=
=9Cbuy and sell quickly to capitalize on small temporary mispricings.=E2=80=
=9D
Also, again, technology has improved, and probably what you have actually=
=C2=A0done is program a computer to recognize patterns in the market and pu=
t in these orders for you. Your algorithm might be of the form =E2=80=9Cput=
 in buy and sell orders $0.25 away from the fair price in either direction,=
=E2=80=9D or it might be of the form =E2=80=9Cif the bond falls $0.25 below=
=C2=A0the fair price, buy it, but if it rises $0.25 above the fair price, s=
ell it.=E2=80=9D But those are the same algorithm.
And you can end up doing this as your entire business, or you can do some o=
f it alongside your normal investor-y business of making longer-term=C2=A0d=
irectional bets on bonds that you think will go up. And you can evolve over=
 time to do more of one or the other as markets change or as you hire diffe=
rent personnel or whatever.
And you can do all this=C2=A0without=C2=A0advertising. You don=E2=80=99t ha=
ve to be in a customer service business; you don=E2=80=99t have to hang out=
 a big sign saying =E2=80=9CWe Buy And Sell Bonds, Call Us!=E2=80=9D Nobody=
 calls anyone anymore.
  [4]
=C2=A0You just send little electronic messages to the trading platform, say=
ing the prices at which you want to buy or sell bonds, and that is all the =
advertising you need.
You could=C2=A0get into customer service =E2=80=94=C2=A0if you start doing =
enough of this sort of trading, you might decide to set up meetings with bi=
g investors to see what they want to buy and sell and to try to trade with =
them more =E2=80=94 and some firms do, but it is not strictly necessary. Yo=
u can have the=C2=A0trading model of=C2=A0a dealer (making markets, providi=
ng liquidity, making the bid/ask spread)=C2=A0without the traditional=C2=A0=
business model=C2=A0of a dealer (salespeople, customer service, advertising=
).
In other words, in the olden days, there was a distinction between dealers,=
 who provided liquidity and advertised, and investors, who made directional=
 bets=C2=A0and did not advertise. Now, there are dealers who provide liquid=
ity and advertise, and investors who make directional bets and don=E2=80=99=
t advertise, and also some other people (quasi-dealers?) who provide liquid=
ity and don=E2=80=99t advertise, and some people (investor-dealers?) who so=
metimes provide liquidity and other times just make directional bets and ne=
ver advertise. The distinctions are less sharp, because modern technology l=
ets everyone do a little of everything and change their strategies as circu=
mstances change.
I mostly just think this is=C2=A0sort of an interesting sociological fact, =
that the trading model of providing liquidity has become much more anonymou=
s and electronic and divorced from the social model of having drinks with c=
ustomers, and that non-traditional dealers can now do it. And it is probabl=
y good for competition: If everyone can compete to buy from sellers and sel=
l to buyers, then the costs of liquidity should go down.
But there is a news hook. The US Securities and Exchange Commission=C2=A0re=
gulates dealers=C2=A0more strictly than it regulates regular investors. Dea=
lers have to register with the SEC and be members of self-regulatory organi=
zations (mainly the stock exchanges and=C2=A0Finra); they are subject to va=
rious risk and capital and recordkeeping rules. It is more expensive to be =
an SEC-registered dealer than not to be.
In the olden days, this was=C2=A0pretty straightforward: If you wanted to g=
o around advertising your bond-dealing services, you had to register with t=
he SEC, and the SEC would keep an eye on you to make sure that you were doi=
ng a fine upstanding job of serving investors and not blowing yourself up. =
The investors were the customers, and the SEC protected them; the dealers w=
ere the industry, and the SEC regulated them.
But now the distinction is much less clear, and yesterday the SEC  publishe=
d new rules about who is and isn=E2=80=99t a dealer. The old rule =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0in the text of  the Securities Exchange Act of 1934 =E2=80=94=C2=A0sa=
ys that =E2=80=9Cthe term =E2=80=98dealer=E2=80=99 means any person engaged=
