n=E2=80=99s own account,=E2=80=9D=C2=A0unless=C2=A0that person =E2=80=9Cbuy=
s or sells securities =E2=80=A6 for such person=E2=80=99s own account, eith=
er individually or in a fiduciary capacity, but not as a part of a regular =
business.=E2=80=9D
  [5]
=C2=A0(Emphasis added.)
In 1934 everyone kind of knew what that meant: If you bought securities and=
 held them, you were not buying and selling =E2=80=9Cas part of a regular b=
usiness,=E2=80=9D but if you went around advertising =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99ll =
buy or sell bonds, call me,=E2=80=9D you were. In 2024 things are less clea=
r, so the SEC wants to clarify them.  The new rules say:

A person that is engaged in buying and selling securities for its own accou=
nt is engaged in such activity =E2=80=9Cas a part of a regular business=E2=
=80=9D =E2=80=A6 if that person:
(1) Engages in a regular pattern of buying and selling securities that has =
the effect of providing liquidity to other market participants by:=C2=A0
(i) Regularly expressing trading interest that is at or near the best avail=
able prices on both sides of the market for the same security and that is c=
ommunicated and represented in a way that makes it accessible to other mark=
et participants; or
(ii) Earning revenue primarily from capturing bid-ask spreads, by buying at=
 the bid and selling at the offer, or from capturing any incentives offered=
 by trading venues to liquidity-supplying trading interest.

There are exceptions, including for central banks, registered investment co=
mpanies (mutual funds) and people with under $50 million of assets. But the=
