 X at $77.75 or sell it at $78.25=E2=80=9D), or if they make money mostly f=
rom bid-ask spreads, then they are dealers.
This strikes me as more or less conceptually correct, in the narrow sense: =
Yes, making two-sided markets and collecting the spread is the traditional =
model of the dealer, and this definition is clearer than the =E2=80=9Cregul=
ar business=E2=80=9D=C2=A0thing.
In the broader sense, it strikes me as a bit incoherent: Why=C2=A0should pe=
ople who make two-sided markets be regulated more strictly than people who =
make directional bets? The old reason =E2=80=94=C2=A0the dealers were the i=
ndustry and the directional bettors were the customers =E2=80=94=C2=A0is no=
 longer really true.
The apparent reason is something like =E2=80=9Cfirms that run dealer-type s=
trategies in the Treasury bond market are much more=C2=A0levered=C2=A0than =
firms that just buy and hold Treasury bonds.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0SEC Chair Gary G=
ensler=E2=80=99s=C2=A0statement about the new rules reminisces about old-ti=
me Treasury dealer collapses, and goes on:

In 2021, when I arrived at the SEC, I was told that though numerous firms h=
ave registered with the SEC as government securities dealers, some market p=
articipants have not. I think that leaves potential regulatory gaps and ris=
