  [1] The US Securities and Exchange literature  sometimes calls them =E2=
=80=9Cdealers=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Ctraders,=E2=80=9D but =E2=80=9Ctrader=
=E2=80=9D to me feels more generic; a =E2=80=9Ctrader=E2=80=9D at a bank is=
 ordinarily a dealer. =E2=80=9CInvestor=E2=80=9D is imperfect because it ha=
s a bit of a long-term connotation, which I don=E2=80=99t intend. =E2=80=9C=
Speculator=E2=80=9D would be fine for =E2=80=9Cinvestor=E2=80=9D but people=
 sometimes take it as pejorative. =E2=80=9CMarket maker=E2=80=9D is, I thin=
k, generally a good synonym for =E2=80=9Cdealer.=E2=80=9D


  [2] Perhaps some markets are totally disintermediated and fundamental inv=
estors just trade with each other. But many markets are intermediated only =
by brokers, not dealers: The brokers match up the fundamental buyers and se=
llers, but do not trade for their own account. These patterns are not alway=
s stable. US single-family housing has historically been almost entirely a =
broker-intermediated market: The person who owns a house usually lives ther=
e (or owns it as a long-term investment), and then sells it to someone else=
 who wants to live there (or own it as an investment). There are brokers to=
 match buyers and sellers, who take a cut, but the brokers don=E2=80=99t *b=
uy* the house from the seller with their own money and then sell it to the =
buyer. But that has changed a little bit, with e.g. Zillow Group Inc. getti=
ng into (and then out of)   algorithmic house market-making in recent years=
.


  [3] Or it won=E2=80=99t, it will have hidden orders, etc., but in any cas=
e your orders will have some way of interacting with other people=E2=80=99s=
 orders.


  [4] I am exaggerating for simplicity; in the bond markets lots of people =
call each other. The text more accurately describes Treasury trading than, =
like, high-yield corporate trading. But even in Treasuries people use the p=
hone, or at least Bloomberg chats.


  [5] There is a similar definition of =E2=80=9Cgovernment securities deale=
r,=E2=80=9D which is not the same thing as a regular =E2=80=9Cdealer=E2=80=
=9D but is a parallel definition for Treasury bonds. And this one is probab=
ly more important for this week=E2=80=99s rulemaking, which seems *primaril=
y* focused on Treasury trading.


  [6] The lawyer is Alex Spiro, who is also Elon Musk=E2=80=99s lawyer, and=
 who seems to have a lot of fun.


