<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Dealers</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In the olden days, there were two sorts of peo=
ple who traded stocks or bonds for a living. We can call them =E2=80=9Cdeal=
ers=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cinvestors,=E2=80=9D though those terms are imperf=
ect.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #00000=
0; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-botto=
m-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: t=
ransparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a> An investor is someone who buys stocks or bonds because she thinks the=
y are a good investment, and sells them when she thinks they aren=E2=80=99t=
. She does=C2=A0analysis, decides that Bond X is worth $80,=C2=A0sees it tr=
ading at $78, and goes out to buy some Bond X. When it trades up to $82, sh=
e sells it. She makes her money by buying low and selling high, by predicti=
ng price trends or understanding fundamental value. Investors include ordin=
ary retail investors, but mutual funds and hedge funds are also in this cat=
egory. Their job is to buy stuff that they think will go up.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A dealer is the person the investors buy from=
=C2=A0and sell to. A dealer is not looking to buy stocks or bonds that she =
thinks are a good investment, or to sell ones that she thinks are a bad inv=
estment. A bond dealer has some list of bonds, and she is always willing to=
 buy or sell each of those=C2=A0bonds. She is in a customer service busines=
s: Customers come to her looking to buy or sell bonds, and she sells them t=
he bonds they want to buy and buys the bonds they want to sell. She makes m=
oney not by predicting price moves=C2=A0but by charging the customers (inve=
stors) a bit of money (called the =E2=80=9Cspread=E2=80=9D) for each trade,=
 buying from them at a lower price (her =E2=80=9Cbid=E2=80=9D) than she wil=
l sell to them (her =E2=80=9Coffer=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cask=E2=80=9D).=C2=
=A0An investor thinks =E2=80=9CBond X trades at $78 and is worth $80, so I =
will buy it.=E2=80=9D A dealer thinks =E2=80=9CBond X trades at $78, so I w=
ill buy it at $77.75 or sell it at $78.25, whichever customers want.=E2=80=
=9D She doesn=E2=80=99t care what it=E2=80=99s worth. She cares about charg=
ing a bit more to sell than she pays to buy.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Investors could theoretically exist without de=
alers, and in some markets they do.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#foo=
tnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-=
bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none =
!important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block=
;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a> Investors who think that Bond X is worth $80 could just buy it from in=
vestors who think it=E2=80=99s worth $75, without a middleman. But in pract=
ice it is often helpful for there to be a middleman =E2=80=94=C2=A0a dealer=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0to =E2=80=9Cprovide liquidity.=E2=80=9D An investor who thi=
nks Bond X is worth $80 probably wants to buy it=C2=A0<em>now</em>; an inve=
stor who thinks it is worth $75 probably wants to sell it <em>now</em>.=C2=
=A0If they each come to that conclusion at exactly the same time, they can =
trade with each other and that=E2=80=99s great. But if the seller decides t=
o sell an hour before the buyer decides to buy, it is helpful for there to =
be a middleman to buy from the seller and sell to the buyer. And the seller=
 and buyer might each be happy to pay $0.25 to get what they want when they=
 want it.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In the olden days the dealer also provided an =
even more important service, which is that you knew where to find her. She =
was in the <em>business </em>of dealing stocks or bonds. She made her money=
 by having lots of customers. She <em>advertised</em>. She <em>wanted</em> =
you to call her to buy or sell bonds. Dealers were traditionally big broker=
age firms and investment banks; they=C2=A0took big investors out for drinks=
 to get to know them and win their business. Before, like, the internet, if=
 some investor owned Bond X and thought it was worth $75 and wanted to sell=
 it, and some other investor didn=E2=80=99t own Bond X and thought it was w=
orth $80 and wanted to buy it, how would they=C2=A0<em>know </em>about each=
 other? They wouldn=E2=80=99t. The investor who owned Bond X would call the=
 dealer and sell to her, and the investor who wanted Bond X would call the =
dealer and buy from her, because they had the dealer=E2=80=99s phone number=
 and knew she would be happy to buy or sell.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This was pretty true about the=C2=A0<em>bond=
=C2=A0</em>market, but less true about the stock market. In the stock marke=
t there were (and are!)=C2=A0<em>exchanges</em>, where all the investors co=
uld meet up and buy and sell stocks. Investors could put=C2=A0<em>orders </=
em>into the stock market, saying =E2=80=9CI want to buy 100 shares of Stock=
 Y for $78,=E2=80=9D and if some other investor put an order in saying =E2=
=80=9CI want to sell 100 shares of Stock Y for $78=E2=80=9D then they could=
=C2=A0trade with each other without involving a dealer at all. In practice =
stock exchanges normally do involve dealers, because there is often some im=
balance between investors who want to buy and those who want to sell. But a=
t least the exchange is a way of coordinating investor buyers and investor =
sellers without having to=C2=A0call<em>=C2=A0</em>a dealer. If you wanted t=
o sell a bond, you knew to call Bear Stearns or Lehman Brothers or whoever;=
 if you wanted to sell a New York Stock Exchange-listed=C2=A0stock, you kne=
w to send an order to NYSE. (In practice you would do that through a=C2=A0<=
em>broker</em>=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0like Bear Stearns or Lehman Brothers =E2=
=80=94 because you couldn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0just stroll out on the floor of th=
e stock exchange, but still.)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But at least in the bond markets=C2=A0there wa=
s a pretty clear distinction between investors and dealers, which is that d=
ealers advertised =E2=80=9CWe Buy And Sell Bonds, Call Us!=E2=80=9D and inv=
estors did not.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But then the internet arrived, communications =
technology became vastly better, and everything went electronic. And now if=
 you want to buy or sell bonds =E2=80=94=C2=A0or currencies, or interest-ra=
te swaps, or cryptocurrencies, etc. =E2=80=94 you can often go to some elec=
tronic platform and put in an order, just like you would on the stock excha=
nge. And that platform will collect your orders, and the orders of lots of =
other people, and it will show the orders to everyone else on the platform<=
a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; te=
xt-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-col=
or: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transp=
arent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>=C2=A0and match up buyers and sellers. You don=E2=80=99t need to rememb=
er =E2=80=9CI want to sell bonds and I happen to know Morgan Stanley is in =
the business of buying bonds, I should call them.=E2=80=9D You can just typ=
e =E2=80=9CSell bonds at $78=E2=80=9D into the electronic system and Morgan=
 Stanley=C2=A0or BlackRock or Pimco or Fidelity or Citadel Securities or an=
yone else can buy them.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One possible outcome of this widespread electr=
onification would be that investors would trade directly with investors and=
 dealers would wither away in bond (currency, swaps, crypto, etc.) markets.=
 There would be no bid/ask spreads, no intermediation; long-term owners wou=
ld sell directly to other long-term owners at the mid-market=C2=A0price. Yo=
u often see predictions like this, but they rarely come true. Even in open =
electronic all-to-all markets, dealers seem to provide some value by buying=
 immediately when investors want to sell and selling immediately when inves=
tors want to buy. And investors are generally willing to pay a spread to ge=
t that immediacy.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But another, maybe more surprising outcome is =
that investors=C2=A0<em>can be dealers now</em>. If you run a hedge fund an=
d try to buy bonds that you think will go up, and you connect to an electro=
nic trading platform and trade a lot on it, you might notice some short-ter=
m opportunities. You know Bond X is trading at $78, you think it=E2=80=99s =
worth $80, but someone comes onto the platform with an order to buy a lot o=
f Bond X. You might say =E2=80=9Cwell okay I=E2=80=99ll sell her some Bond =
X at $78.25, because she=E2=80=99s desperate to buy it now and will pay a b=
it more than the current market price, and then in 10 minutes someone else =
will come along looking to sell it and I=E2=80=99ll buy it back from him at=
 $77.75 and make a quick 50 cents.=E2=80=9D Maybe you also have a big long-=
term investment position in Bond X that you won=E2=80=99t close out until i=
t hits $80, but you know that people make money by buying at the bid and se=
lling at the offer and collecting the spread, and you figure you can do a l=
ittle bit of that too.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You can conceive of this as =E2=80=9Cdealing,=
=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cmarket making,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Ccollecting the sp=
read.=E2=80=9D You can do what dealers do, and put=C2=A0<em>orders=C2=A0</e=
m>into the electronic platform on <em>both sides</em> of the market: You ca=
n put in an order to buy 100 bonds at $77.75 and another order to sell 100 =
bonds at $78.25 and hope that both of those orders will be executed and you=
=E2=80=99ll collect=C2=A0the spread. But you can also conceive of it in oth=
er ways. You can think of it as just short-term day-trading, just spotting =
opportunities, just buying low (from someone looking to unload bonds at a b=
it below the fair market price) and selling high (minutes earlier or later,=
 to someone looking to buy bonds at a bit above the fair market price). The=
re is some continuum between =E2=80=9Cput in orders on both sides of the ma=
rket to collect the spread=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cbuy and sell quickly to ca=
pitalize on small temporary mispricings.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also, again, technology has improved, and prob=
ably what you have actually=C2=A0done is program a computer to recognize pa=
tterns in the market and put in these orders for you. Your algorithm might =
be of the form =E2=80=9Cput in buy and sell orders $0.25 away from the fair=
 price in either direction,=E2=80=9D or it might be of the form =E2=80=9Cif=
 the bond falls $0.25 below=C2=A0the fair price, buy it, but if it rises $0=
.25 above the fair price, sell it.=E2=80=9D But those are the same algorith=
m.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And you can end up doing this as your entire b=
usiness, or you can do some of it alongside your normal investor-y business=
 of making longer-term=C2=A0directional bets on bonds that you think will g=
o up. And you can evolve over time to do more of one or the other as market=
s change or as you hire different personnel or whatever.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And you can do all this=C2=A0<em>without=C2=A0=
</em>advertising. You don=E2=80=99t have to be in a customer service busine=
ss; you don=E2=80=99t have to hang out a big sign saying =E2=80=9CWe Buy An=
d Sell Bonds, Call Us!=E2=80=9D Nobody calls anyone anymore.<a class=3D"foo=
tnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration:=
 none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; b=
order-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !importa=
nt; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a>=C2=A0You just send little electronic messages to the trading platform,=
 saying the prices at which you want to buy or sell bonds, and that is all =
the advertising you need.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You <em>could=C2=A0</em>get into customer serv=
ice =E2=80=94=C2=A0if you start doing enough of this sort of trading, you m=
ight decide to set up meetings with big investors to see what they want to =
buy and sell and to try to trade with them more =E2=80=94 and some firms do=
, but it is not strictly necessary. You can have the=C2=A0<em>trading model=
 </em>of=C2=A0a dealer (making markets, providing liquidity, making the bid=
/ask spread)=C2=A0without the traditional=C2=A0<em>business model=C2=A0</em=
>of a dealer (salespeople, customer service, advertising).</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In other words, in the olden days, there was a=
 distinction between dealers, who provided liquidity and advertised, and in=
vestors, who made directional bets=C2=A0and did not advertise. Now, there a=
re dealers who provide liquidity and advertise, and investors who make dire=
ctional bets and don=E2=80=99t advertise, and also some other people (quasi=
-dealers?) who provide liquidity and don=E2=80=99t advertise, and some peop=
le (investor-dealers?) who sometimes provide liquidity and other times just=
 make directional bets and never advertise. The distinctions are less sharp=
, because modern technology lets everyone do a little of everything and cha=
nge their strategies as circumstances change.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I mostly just think this is=C2=A0sort of an in=
teresting sociological fact, that the trading model of providing liquidity =
has become much more anonymous and electronic and divorced from the social =
model of having drinks with customers, and that non-traditional dealers can=
 now do it. And it is probably good for competition: If everyone can compet=
e to buy from sellers and sell to buyers, then the costs of liquidity shoul=
d go down.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But there is a news hook. The US Securities an=
d Exchange Commission=C2=A0<em>regulates dealers=C2=A0</em>more strictly th=
an it regulates regular investors. Dealers have to register with the SEC an=
d be members of self-regulatory organizations (mainly the stock exchanges a=
nd=C2=A0Finra); they are subject to various risk and capital and recordkeep=
ing rules. It is more expensive to be an SEC-registered dealer than not to =
be.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In the olden days, this was=C2=A0pretty straig=
htforward: If you wanted to go around advertising your bond-dealing service=
s, you had to register with the SEC, and the SEC would keep an eye on you t=
o make sure that you were doing a fine upstanding job of serving investors =
and not blowing yourself up. The investors were the customers, and the SEC =
protected them; the dealers were the industry, and the SEC regulated them.<=
/p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But now the distinction is much less clear, an=
d yesterday the SEC <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/clic=
k/34269974.257392/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3ByZXNzLXJlbGVhc2UvMjAyN=
C0xNA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe4084ac4" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> published new rules</a>=
 about who is and isn=E2=80=99t a dealer. The old rule =E2=80=94=C2=A0in th=
e text of <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34269974=
.257392/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubGF3LmNvcm5lbGwuZWR1L3VzY29kZS90ZXh0LzE1Lzc4Yw/607f=
07ceef4b8524a319a23cB229ae1d7" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscop=
e" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !import=
ant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-=
style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> the Securities Exchange Act of 1934=
</a> =E2=80=94=C2=A0says that =E2=80=9Cthe term =E2=80=98dealer=E2=80=99 me=
ans any person engaged in the business of buying and selling securities .=
=E2=80=A6 for such person=E2=80=99s own account,=E2=80=9D=C2=A0<em>unless=
=C2=A0</em>that person =E2=80=9Cbuys or sells securities =E2=80=A6 for such=
 person=E2=80=99s own account, either individually or in a fiduciary capaci=
ty, <em>but not as a part of a regular business</em>.=E2=80=9D<a class=3D"f=
ootnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-5" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoratio=
n: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000;=
 border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !impor=
tant; display: inline-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a>=C2=A0(Emphasis added.)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In 1934 everyone kind of knew what that meant:=
 If you bought securities and held them, you were not buying and selling =
=E2=80=9Cas part of a regular business,=E2=80=9D but if you went around adv=
ertising =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99ll buy or sell bonds, call me,=E2=80=9D you wer=
e. In 2024 things are less clear, so the SEC wants to clarify them. <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34269974.257392/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9maWxlcy9ydWxlcy9maW5hbC8yMDI0LzM0LTk5NDc3LnBkZg/607f07cee=
f4b8524a319a23cBd9989680" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" ta=
rget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; =
border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style=
: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> The new rules say</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A person that is engaged in buying and selling=
 securities for its own account is engaged in such activity =E2=80=9Cas a p=
art of a regular business=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6 if that person:</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">(1) Engages in a regular pattern of buying and=
 selling securities that has the effect of providing liquidity to other mar=
ket participants by:=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">(i) Regularly expressing trading interest that=
 is at or near the best available prices on both sides of the market for th=
e same security and that is communicated and represented in a way that make=
s it accessible to other market participants; or</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">(ii) Earning revenue primarily from capturing =
bid-ask spreads, by buying at the bid and selling at the offer, or from cap=
turing any incentives offered by trading venues to liquidity-supplying trad=
ing interest.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are exceptions, including for central ba=
nks, registered investment companies (mutual funds) and people with under $=
50 million of assets. But the point of this is pretty clearly to capture he=
dge funds and proprietary trading firms that make markets (often electronic=
ally) in bond markets, particularly Treasury markets. If those firms regula=
rly post interest on both sides of the market=C2=A0(if they regularly say =
=E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99ll buy Bond X at $77.75 or sell it at $78.25=E2=80=9D), =
or if they make money mostly from bid-ask spreads, then they are dealers.</=
p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This strikes me as more or less conceptually c=
orrect, in the narrow sense: Yes, making two-sided markets and collecting t=
he spread is the traditional model of the dealer, and this definition is cl=
earer than the =E2=80=9Cregular business=E2=80=9D=C2=A0thing.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In the broader sense, it strikes me as a bit i=
ncoherent: <em>Why=C2=A0</em>should people who make two-sided markets be re=
gulated more strictly than people who make directional bets? The old reason=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0the dealers were the industry and the directional bettors w=
ere the customers =E2=80=94=C2=A0is no longer really true.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The apparent reason is something like =E2=80=
=9Cfirms that run dealer-type strategies in the Treasury bond market are mu=
ch more=C2=A0<em>levered=C2=A0</em>than firms that just buy and hold Treasu=
ry bonds.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/=
click/34269974.257392/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3N0YXRlbWVudC9nZW5zb=
GVyLXN0YXRlbWVudC1kZWFsZXItdHJhZGVyLTAyMDYyNA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc67c=
e565" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" styl=
e=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width:=
 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-=
color: #ccc;">SEC Chair Gary Gensler=E2=80=99s=C2=A0statement</a> about the=
 new rules reminisces about old-time Treasury dealer collapses, and goes on=
:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In 2021, when I arrived at the SEC, I was told=
 that though numerous firms have registered with the SEC as government secu=
rities dealers, some market participants have not. I think that leaves pote=
ntial regulatory gaps and risk in the system.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The markets also have evolved in other ways, s=
uch as electronification, the use of algorithmic trading, and market partic=
ipants transacting faster than ever before. Some market participants, such =
as principal-trading firms (PTFs) that use high-frequency trading strategie=
s, started participating significantly in the Treasury cash market. In 2019=
, for example, PTFs represented around 60 percent of the volume on the inte=
r-dealer broker (IDB) platforms in the Treasury markets.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In essence, these PTFs and other firms are act=
ing in a manner consistent with dealers in the securities markets. Neverthe=
less, despite these firms acting as de facto market makers, and despite the=
ir regularity of participation consistent with buying and selling securitie=
s or government securities =E2=80=9Cas a part of a regular business,=E2=80=
=9D a number of these firms have not registered with the Commission as deal=
ers.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This deprives investors and the markets themse=
lves of important protections=E2=80=94protections that benefit market integ=
rity, resiliency, transparency, and more.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I suppose there is some truth to this, that th=
e trading business of making markets in Treasury bonds tends to be more lev=
eraged than the investing business of buying Treasuries because you think t=
hey are valuable. But it=E2=80=99s still pretty porous. The <a href=3D"http=
s://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34269974.257392/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud=
3NqLmNvbS9maW5hbmNlL3JlZ3VsYXRpb24vc2VjLWluY3JlYXNlcy1vdmVyc2lnaHQtZm9yLWhl=
ZGdlLWZ1bmRzLWhpZ2gtc3BlZWQtdHJhZGVycy04NGE0Mzc0OT9tb2Q9aXRwX3dzag/607f07ce=
ef4b8524a319a23cB744fef22" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" t=
arget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Wall Street Journal reports</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">An earlier version of the SEC=E2=80=99s dealer=
 rule would have likely roped in many large hedge funds. Any person or firm=
 that bought or sold more than $25 billion in government bonds in four of t=
he preceding six months would have automatically been classified as a secur=
ities dealer under a March 2022 proposal from the SEC. So would firms that =
routinely made =E2=80=9Croughly comparable=E2=80=9D purchases or sales of s=
imilar securities in one day.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Hedge funds and their trade groups howled at t=
he proposal and felt it threatened the profitability of investing strategie=
s like quant, arbitrage and relative-value trading, which seeks to capitali=
ze on pricing discrepancies between different securities.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In comments submitted to the SEC, hedge-fund f=
irms argued that requiring them to register as dealers would deprive them o=
f certain investor protections. They argued there would be unintended conse=
quences, including the prevention of them from participating in initial pub=
lic offerings. Hedge-fund firms also complained that the SEC was exempting =
mutual funds and other types of asset managers from the additional requirem=
ents.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The SEC ultimately scrapped the $25 billion th=
reshold and some other parts that the industry criticized. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0N=
evertheless, an SEC analysis identified up to 16 private funds, a category =
that includes hedge funds, that could fit its revised definition of a deale=
r, an agency official said at the meeting.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The basic business is using borrowed money to=
=C2=A0buy=C2=A0and sell=C2=A0lots of Treasuries, fairly quickly, because yo=
u have a computer model that tries to take advantage of pricing discrepanci=
es. If those pricing discrepancies are bid/ask spreads, you=E2=80=99re a de=
aler; if they=E2=80=99re not, you=E2=80=99re not.=C2=A0</p>
